                <h1>Understanding Jordan Baker in The Great Gatsby</h1>
                <p>Jordan Baker, a key character in F. Scott Fitzgerald's "The Great Gatsby," embodies the themes of wealth, dishonesty, and the complexities of modern relationships in the Roaring Twenties. A skilled golfer and friend of Daisy Buchanan, Jordan is both alluring and enigmatic, reflecting the moral ambiguity of the era. Her interactions with Gatsby reveal the contrast between ambition and authenticity.</p>
